      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics of originalism argue that it's impractical and often overly rigid. They contend that the original intent or meaning of the framers is difficult, if not impossible, to ascertain with any certainty. This approach also fails to account for the evolution of society and changes in moral and social norms, potentially leading to outdated or unjust interpretations of the Constitution. Furthermore, critics argue that originalism can impede progress by preventing the adaptation of constitutional principles to contemporary issues. Lastly, opponents claim that originalism can be used to justify decisions that benefit a specific political agenda, undermining the impartiality of the judiciary.",
      "source": "target",
